<p>While medically necessary eye care is fully covered, corrective devices like eyeglasses and contact lenses receive limited NHS support. The NHS does not automatically provide free eyeglasses or contact lenses for refractive errors; instead, you receive an eyeglass prescription that you fill through private opticians at your own expense. Children, elderly individuals, and low-income patients may qualify for limited NHS eyeglass assistance, but working-age expats typically pay privately. Eyeglass costs in Italy vary widely depending on frame selection and lens options. Budget opticians in Italian cities offer basic frames and standard lenses for 30-50 euros per pair. Mid-range frames with progressive lenses (bifocals) cost 80-150 euros. Designer frames and specialized lenses like transition lenses, anti-reflective coatings, or high-index lenses for strong prescriptions range from 150-400+ euros. Contact lenses similarly require private payment; daily disposable contacts cost approximately 20-30 euros per box of 30 lenses in Italy. Comparison shopping between Italian optical chains (like Ottica Plus or local independent opticians) helps minimize corrective device costs.</p>

