<p>Between 12 and 24 months, children receive booster vaccinations reinforcing immunity from earlier doses. At 12 months, infants typically receive meningococcal C vaccine and varicella (chickenpox) vaccine as their first dose. At 18 months, booster doses of hexavalent vaccine are given, and some regions provide meningococcal B vaccine at this time. Between 18 months and 2 years, second dose of varicella vaccine is administered. At approximately 5-6 years of age, before school entry, children receive booster doses of tetanus, diphtheria, pertussis, and polio vaccines (5-6 year boosters). At 11-12 years of age, meningococcal A, C, W135, and Y vaccine (MCV4) is typically administered. Human papillomavirus (HPV) vaccine is given to adolescents, typically at 11-12 years for girls and increasingly for boys as well. The schedule's timing ensures children have maximum protection before entering school environments where infectious disease exposure increases. Italian pediatricians provide careful scheduling and reminders to ensure appointments aren't missed; many pediatric practices use email or SMS reminders for upcoming vaccinations.</p>

