<p>Expats can access influenza vaccination through multiple channels in Italy. Your medico di base (family physician) can administer influenza vaccine during routine office visits, often without requiring a specific appointment if you call ahead. The local health department (ASL—Azienda Sanitaria Locale) operates influenza vaccination clinics during the vaccination season, open to all registered residents. Many Italian pharmacies (farmacie) now administer influenza vaccines, providing convenient access without requiring a physician appointment. Some occupational health services administer flu vaccines for workplace employees. The Italian NHS covers influenza vaccine costs for eligible individuals (typically those aged 60+, healthcare workers, pregnant women, those with chronic conditions), with no or minimal copayments. Individuals outside recommended groups can still receive vaccine through the NHS at minimal cost, or through private channels. This multiple-access approach ensures virtually everyone in Italy can obtain influenza vaccination conveniently. Ask at your local farmacia whether they offer flu vaccination; if so, you can walk in during their vaccination hours and receive vaccination immediately without physician referral.</p>

