<p>If you experience potential hepatitis B exposure through needlestick, mucous membrane contact with blood, or unprotected sexual contact with someone with hepatitis B, post-exposure prophylaxis (PEP) can prevent infection if administered promptly. PEP involves hepatitis B vaccine and hepatitis B immune globulin (HBIG) administered within 24 hours of exposure, ideally sooner. Occupational exposures (healthcare workers) warrant immediate evaluation and PEP initiation; contact your occupational health services or emergency department. Non-occupational exposures (sexual assault, consensual unprotected sexual contact with positive partner) similarly warrant immediate medical evaluation. Time-sensitive nature of PEP makes rapid access to emergency medical evaluation critical. Discussing hepatitis B vaccination with your medico di base before potential occupational exposure ensures you're protected and understand steps to take if exposure occurs.</p>

